defs.docs: ftp is an FTP client written in Rust.

defs.name: FtpStream
defs.docs: Stream to interface with the FTP server. This interface is only for the command stream.

defs.name: connect
defs.docs: Creates an FTP Stream.

defs.name: get_ref
defs.docs: Returns a reference to the underlying TcpStream.

defs.name: login
defs.docs: Log in to the FTP server.

defs.name: cwd
defs.docs: Change the current directory to the path specified.

defs.name: cdup
defs.docs: Move the current directory to the parent directory.

defs.name: pwd
defs.docs: Gets the current directory

defs.name: noop
defs.docs: This does nothing. This is usually just used to keep the connection open.

defs.name: mkdir
defs.docs: This creates a new directory on the server.

defs.name: transfer_type
defs.docs:
Sets the type of file to be transferred. That is the implementation
 of `TYPE` command.

defs.name: quit
defs.docs: Quits the current FTP session.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Retrieves the file name specified from the server.
 This method is a more complicated way to retrieve a file.
 The reader returned should be dropped.
 Also you will have to read the response to make sure it has the correct value.

defs.name: rename
defs.docs: Renames the file from_name to to_name

defs.name: retr
defs.value: fn <F, T> (&mut self, filename: &str, reader: F) -> Result<T>
defs.docs:
The implementation of `RETR` command where `filename` is the name of the file
 to download from FTP and `reader` is the function which operates with the
 data stream opened.

defs.name: simple_retr
defs.docs: Simple way to retr a file from the server. This stores the file in memory.

defs.name: rmdir
defs.docs: Removes the remote pathname from the server.

defs.name: rm
defs.docs: Remove the remote file from the server.

defs.name: put
defs.value: fn <R> (&mut self, filename: &str, r: &mut R) -> Result<()>
defs.docs: This stores a file on the server.

defs.name: list
defs.docs:
Execute `LIST` command which returns the detailed file listing in human readable format.
 If `pathname` is omited then the list of files in the current directory will be
 returned otherwise it will the list of files on `pathname`.

defs.name: nlst
defs.docs:
Execute `NLST` command which returns the list of file names only.
 If `pathname` is omited then the list of files in the current directory will be
 returned otherwise it will the list of files on `pathname`.

defs.name: mdtm
defs.docs:
Retrieves the modification time of the file at `pathname` if it exists.
 In case the file does not exist `None` is returned.

defs.name: size
defs.docs:
Retrieves the size of the file in bytes at `pathname` if it exists.
 In case the file does not exist `None` is returned.

defs.name: read_response_in
defs.docs: Retrieve single line response

defs.name: DataStream
defs.docs: Data Stream used for communications

defs.name: get_ref
defs.docs: Returns a reference to the underlying TcpStream.

defs.name: types
defs.docs: The set of valid values for FTP commands

defs.name: Result
defs.docs: A shorthand for a Result whose error type is always an FtpError.

defs.name: FtpError
defs.docs:
`FtpError` is a library-global error type to describe the different kinds of
 errors that might occur while using FTP.

defs.name: Default
defs.docs: Default text format control (is NonPrint)

defs.name: NonPrint
defs.docs: Non-print (not destined for printing)

defs.name: Telnet
defs.docs: Telnet format control (\<CR\>, \<FF\>, etc.)

defs.name: Asa
defs.docs: ASA (Fortran) Carriage Control

defs.name: FormatControl
defs.docs: Text Format Control used in `TYPE` command

defs.name: Ascii
defs.docs: ASCII text (the argument is the text format control)

defs.name: Ebcdic
defs.docs: EBCDIC text (the argument is the text format control)

defs.name: Image
defs.docs: Image,

defs.name: Binary
defs.docs: Binary (the synonym to Image)

defs.name: Local
defs.docs: Local format (the argument is the number of bits in one byte on local machine)

defs.name: FileType
defs.docs: File Type used in `TYPE` command

defs.name: Line
defs.docs: `Line` contains a command code and the contents of a line of text read from the network.
